lank1_info            =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              =\n}} <!-- Infobox ends -->\n\nThe '''Grand Rapids metropolitan area''' is a triangular shaped Metro Triplex, in [[Western Michigan|West Michigan]], which fans out westward from the primary hub city of [[Grand Rapids]], [[Michigan]] to the other two metro hubs of [[Muskegon, MI|Muskegon]] and [[Holland, MI|Holland]]. The [[metropolitan statistical area|metropolitan area]] has an estimated population of 1,059,113 as of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Annual Estimates of the Resident Population: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2016 - United States -- Metropolitan and Micropolitan Statistical Area; and for Puerto Rico|url=https://www.census.gov|website=American FactFidner|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref> The region, noted in particular for its western edge abutting the [[Lake Michigan]] shoreline and its beaches, is a popular tourist and vacation destination during the summer. Noted popular metro area beach towns include [[Grand Haven, MI|Grand Haven]], [[Holland, MI|Holland]], [[Muskegon, MI|Muskegon]], and [[Saugatuck, MI|Saugatuck]].\n\nThe metropolitan area is home to many attractions. [[Frederik Meijer Gardens & Sculpture Park]] is located in the outskirts of Grand Rapids. [[Michigan's Adventure]] theme park is just north of Muskegon, and the [[Grand Rapids Art Museum]] and the [[DeVos Place Convention Center]] are both in downtown Grand Rapids. The [[Grand River (Michigan)|Grand River]] flows through the metropolitan area and is noted for its fishing, kayaking, and canoeing.\n\n==Definitions==\n{{See also|Michigan census statistical areas}}\nThe '''Grand Rapids-Kentwood Metropolitan Statistical Area''', as defined by the [[United States Census Bureau]], is an area consisting of four counties in [[Western Michigan|western]] [[Michigan]], anchored by the cities of [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]] and [[Wyoming, Michigan|Wyoming]]. The MSA has a population of 988,938 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. It comprises four counties which include the central county of [[Kent County, Michigan|Kent]], and the outlying counties of [[Ionia County, Michigan|Ionia]], [[Montcalm County, Michigan|Montcalm]], and [[Ottawa County, Michigan|Ottawa]].<ref name=\"CBSA\">{{cite web |last1=Mulvaney |first1=Mick |title=OMB BULLETIN NO. 18-04 |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Bulletin-18-04.pdf |website=Whitehouse.gov |publisher=Office of Management & Budget |accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Grand Rapids \u2013 Kentwood \u2013 Muskegon Combined Statistical Area''' is the 2nd largest [[combined statistical area|CSA]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]] (behind [[Metro Detroit]]). The CSA had a population of 1,320,064 at the 2010 census. The primary cultural and financial centers of the region are [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]], [[Muskegon, Michigan|Muskegon]] and [[Holland, Michigan|Holland]]. It includes the four counties in the Grand Rapids-Kentwood MSA plus one [[United States metropolitan area|metropolitan area]], adding the Muskegon, MI MSA of [[Muskegon County, Michigan|Muskegon County]], and two [[United States micropolitan area|micropolitan areas]] of Holland of [[Allegan County]], and Big Rapids of [[Mecosta County]] for a total of seven counties.\n\nThe Grand Rapids metropolitan area is part of the [[Great Lakes Megalopolis]] containing an estimated 54 million people.\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:ISS030-E-187833.jpg|thumb|Grand Rapids and nearby cities, taken from the ISS in 2012. Grand Rapids in the upper center and is the largest city. Holland is the large city to the left of Grand Rapids. Beneath Grand Rapids, from left to right are Kalamazoo, Battle Creek, and Lansing, none of which are part of the Grand Rapids metro area.]]\n===Places with more than 50,000 inhabitants===\n* [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]] (Principal city of MSA and CSA)\n* [[Wyoming, Michigan|Wyoming]] (Principal city of MSA)\n* [[Kentwood, Michigan|Kentwood]]\n\n===Places with 20,000 to 50,000 inhabitants===\n* [[Allendale Charter Township, Michigan|Allendale Charter Township]]\n* [[Byron Township, Michigan|Byron Township]]\n* [[Gaines Township, Kent County, Michigan|Gaines Charter Township]]\n* [[Georgetown Township, Michigan|Georgetown Charter Township]]\n* [[Holland, Michigan|Holland]] (Principal city of CSA)\n* [[Holland Charter Township]]\n* [[Muskegon, Michigan|Muskegon]] (Principal city of CSA)\n* [[Norton Shores, Michigan|Norton Shores]]\n* [[Plainfield Township, Kent County, Michigan|Plainfield Charter Township]]\n* [[Walker, Michigan|Walker]]\n\n===Places with 10,000 to 20,000 inhabitants===\n* [[Ada Township, Michigan|Ada Township]]\n* [[Allendale, Michigan|Allendale]] ([[Census-designated place|CDP]])\n* [[Alpine Township, Michigan|Alpine Township]]\n* [[Caledonia Township, Kent County, Michigan|Caledonia Township]]\n* [[Cannon Township, Michigan|Cannon Township]]\n* [[Cascade Township, Michigan|Cascade Charter Township]]\n* [[Comstock Park, Michigan|Comstock Park]] ([[Census-designated place|CDP]])\n* [[Cutlerville, Michigan|Cutlerville]] ([[Census-designated place|CDP]])\n* [[East Grand Rapids, Michigan|East Grand Rapids]]\n* [[Forest Hills, Michigan|Forest Hills]] ([[Census-designated place|CDP]])\n* [[Fruitport Charter Township, Michigan|Fruitport Charter Township]]\n* [[Grand Haven, Michigan|Grand Haven]]\n* [[Grand Haven Charter Township, Michigan|Grand Haven Charter Township]]\n* [[Grand Rapids Charter Township, Michigan|Grand Rapids Charter Township]]\n* [[Grandville, Michigan|Grandville]]\n* [[Ionia, Michigan|Ionia]]\n* [[Jenison, Michigan|Jenison]] ([[Census-designated place|CDP]])\n* [[Muskegon Township, Michigan|Muskegon Charter Township]]\n* [[Muskegon Heights, Michigan|Muskegon Heights]]\n* [[Park Township, Ottawa County, Michigan|Park Township]]\n* [[Northview, Michigan|Northview]] ([[Census-designated place|CDP]])\n* [[Spring Lake Township, Michigan|Spring Lake Township]]\n\n===Places with 5,000 to 10,000 inhabitants===\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Algoma Township, Michigan|Algoma Township]]\n* [[Belding, Michigan|Belding]]\n* [[Blendon Township, Michigan|Blendon Township]]\n* [[Boston Township, Michigan|Boston Township]]\n* [[Courtland Township, Michigan|Courtland Township]]\n* [[Dalton Township, Michigan|Dalton Township]]\n* [[Dorr Township, Michigan|Dorr Township]]\n* [[Egelston Township, Michigan|Egelston Township]]\n* [[Fruitland Township, Michigan|Fruitland Township]]\n* [[Gun Plain Township, Michigan|Gun Plain Township]]\n* [[Hudsonville, Michigan|Hudsonville]]\n* [[Jamestown Charter Township, Michigan|Jamestown Charter Township]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Laketon Township, Michigan|Laketon Township]]\n* [[Laketown Township, Michigan|Laketown Township]]\n* [[Lowell Township, Michigan|Lowell Charter Township]]\n* [[Oakfield Township, Michigan|Oakfield Township]]\n* [[Otsego Township, Michigan|Otsego Township]]\n* [[Robinson Township, Michigan|Robinson Township]]\n* [[Rockford, Michigan|Rockford]]\n* [[Solon Township, Kent County, Michigan|Solon Township]]\n* [[Sparta Township, Michigan|Sparta Township]]\n* [[Tallmadge Township, Michigan|Tallmadge Charter Township]]\n* [[Zeeland, Michigan|Zeeland]]\n* [[Zeeland Charter Township, Michigan|Zeeland Charter Township]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Places with 2,500 to 5,000 inhabitants===\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Allegan, Michigan|Allegan]]\n* [[Allegan Township, Michigan|Allegan Township]]\n* [[Ashland Township, Michigan|Ashland Township]]\n* [[Beechwood, Michigan|Beechwood]] ([[Census-designated place|CDP]])\n* [[Berlin Township, Ionia County, Michigan|Berlin Township]]\n* [[Big Prairie Township, Michigan|Big Prairie Township]]\n* [[Bowne Township, Michigan|Bowne Township]]\n* [[Brooks Township, Michigan|Brooks Township]]\n* [[Byron Center, Michigan|Byron Center]] ([[Census-designated place|CDP]])\n* [[Casco Township, Allegan County, 