{"title_page": "Timarpur", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n''For other places with the same name, see [[Wazirabad (disambiguation)]]''\n{{unsourced|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Timarpur\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = [[Neighbourhoods of Delhi|Neighbourhood]]\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Delhi\n| pushpin_label_position  = left\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in North Delhi, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|28.7011|77.2204|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|Territory]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Delhi]] ([[National Capital Region (India)|National Capital Region]])\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = North India\n| subdivision_type3       = [[List of towns in National Capital Territory of Delhi|Town]]\n| subdivision_name3       = Delhi\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 110054\n| registration_plate      = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n[[File:Timarpur.jpg|thumb|250px| A street in the residential complex of Timarpur]]\n'''Timarpur''' is one of the seven electoral constituencies in North [[Delhi]], [[India]]. It is located near [[University of Delhi]] and has an area under 2 square kilometers. Its population is about 10,000. Timarpur is the first government colony<ref>http://www.delhigovt.nic.in</ref>{{Not in refs|date=July 2019}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019}} situated by the Government of India and is predominantly a government residential area.\n\nThe area includes eight schools, including six senior secondary schools, one primary school, and one special school for intellectually disabled children. \n\nThe health services in Timarpur include the INMAS health center, which is the biggest [[thyroid]] center in [[India]]. A government-owned CGHS dispensary is also present in the area. \n\nTimarpur is well connected to the Delhi Tilak Basumatary service.\n\nThe area also includes a [[DRDO]] complex consisting of both residential and official areas. \n\nIn Timarpur there is a local dairy village of gurjar of Mandaar clan since 1911. In village there around 46 families and 180-220 house in village.  \n\n==Legislature==\nThe legislative assembly of Timarpur is currently (2014-2019) run by the [[Bhartiya Janata Party]]. The legislator of the area is [[Manoj Tiwari]].\n\n==Residence==\n[[File:Timarpur Residential Complex.jpg|thumb|200px|A building in the residential complex of Timarpur]]\nMost of the area is occupied by government flats, although a private colony is also present there. The area includes about 2,000 government flats which are meant for active government servants. A small portion of the area known as Banarsi Das Estate is privately owned. There are two police stations present in the area. Because it is a government residential area, Timarpur includes only a few markets. \n\nBesides being a government-owned area, a wide portion of the area is occupied by people living in slums. The residents in the government and the private sectors often find it difficult to co-operate with people living in slum areas.\n\nThe old market and Timarpur dairy village of Gurjars situated near the flats has a history of more than a hundred years. It was established in 1911.\n\nThe new market situated in Timarpur, just at a walking distance from the old market is the center of festivities during the Hindu festival of [[Dusshera]]. A grand Ramlila is organized there every year during the festival.\n\n==Places to Visit==\nTimarpur also bears the distinction of housing a 100-year-old plus market. The market (known as the Old Market) was established when Delhi was declared the capital during the British Raj in 1911. Yet the market has not seen development.\n\nTimarpur is surrounded by many tourist attractions like the northern ridge near the North Campus of [[University_of_Delhi|Delhi University]]. The area holds a forest where people come to jog and exercise. It was at one time used by the British armed forces during the British Raj. The flagstaff tower there was used by British families as a hiding spot during the Great Indian Mutiny of 1857. The Mutiny Memorial is also situated near the ridge and is an example of the British architecture that was used in India at that time.{{According to whom|date=July 2019}} It was built in memory of the British soldiers who were killed during the mutiny of 1857.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} Next to the Mutiny Memorial, is an Ashoka pillar that was shifted to Delhi by [[Firuz Shah Tughlaq|Feroz Shah Tughlaq]] (a king from the Tughlaq Dynasty).{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nApart from the historic monuments, Choudhary Sweets (now closed), and the Darvesh Restaurant are some of the eating spaces in Timarpur.{{Relevance inline|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe Budh Bazaar, held every Wednesday inside the Central Government Flats, is a center of attraction.\n\nTimarpur dairy village of Gurjars which supplies milk to the number of locals.\n\n==Education and health facilities==\n[[File:Timarpur Park.jpg|thumb|200px|Triangular Park in the Z-Block of Timarpur]]\n\nThe education facilities of Timarpur are moderate. In total, there are eight schools in Timarpur, six of them government-owned and two privately owned. The area is well connected to the University of Delhi.{{According to whom|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe health facilities of Timarpur include the health center of INMAS which is the biggest and the most technically equipped thyroid center in India. However, the area includes only one dispensary{{Clarify|reason=what is meant by a dispensary?|date=July 2019}} owned by the Government of India. There are several privately owned clinics also present there.\n\n===Schools===\n\n* Arya Samaj Mandir\n* Massom Special School\n* Nagar Nigam Vidhyalaya\n* Patrachar Vidhyalaya\n* Sarvodaya Kanya Vidhyalaya\n* Sarvodaya Bal Vidhyalaya\n* Sarvodaya Vidhyalaya Lancers Road\n* Virendra Public School (private)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Delhi]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n''For other places with the same name, see [[Wazirabad (disambiguation)]]''\n{{unsourced|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Timarpur\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = [[Neighbourhoods of Delhi|Neighbourhood]]\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Delhi\n| pushpin_label_position  = left\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in North Delhi, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|28.7011|77.2204|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|Territory]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Delhi]] ([[National Capital Region (India)|National Capital Region]])\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = North India\n| subdivision_type3       = [[List of towns in National Capital Territory of Delhi|Town]]\n| subdivision_name3       = Delhi\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 110054\n| registration_plate      = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n[[File:Timarpur.jpg|thumb|250px| A street in the residential complex of Timarpur]]\n'''Timarpur''' is one of the seven electoral constituencies in North [[Delhi]], [[India]]. It is located near [[University of Delhi]] and has an area under 2 square kilometers. Its population is about 10,000. Timarpur is the first government colony<ref>http://www.delhigovt.nic.in</ref>{{Not in refs|date=July 2019}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019}} situated by the Government of India and is predominantly a government residential area.\n\nThe area includes eight schools, including six senior secondary schools, one primary school, and one special school for intellectually disabled children. \n\nThe health services in Timarpur include the INMAS health center, which is the biggest [[thyroid]] center in [[India]]. A government-owned CGHS dispensary is also present in the area. \n\nTimarpur is well connected to the Delhi Tilak Basumatary service.\n\nThe area also includes a [[DRDO]] complex consisting of both residential and official areas. \n\nIn Timarpur there is local dairy village of gurjar of Mandaar clan since 1911. In village there around 46 families and 180-220 house in village.  \n\n==Legislature==\nThe legislative assembly of Timarpur is currently (2014-2019) run by the [[Bhartiya Janata Party]]. The legislator of the area is [[Manoj Tiwari]].\n\n==Residence==\n[[File:Timarpur Residential Complex.jpg|thumb|200px|A building in the residential complex of Timarpur]]\nMost of the area is occupied by government flats, although a private colony is also present there. The area includes about 2,000 government flats which are meant for active government servants. A small portion of the area known as Banarsi Das Estate is privately owned. There are two police stations present in the area. Because it is a government residential area, Timarpur includes only a few markets. \n\nBesides being a government-owned area, a wide portion of the area is occupied by people living in slums. The residents in the government and the private sectors often find it difficult to co-operate with people living in slum areas.\n\nThe old market and Timarpur dairy village of Gurjars situated near the flats has a history of more than a hundred years. It was established in 1911.\n\nThe new market situated in Timarpur, just at a walking distance from the old market is the center of festivities during the Hindu festival of [[Dusshera]]. A grand Ramlila is organized there every year during the festival.\n\n==Places to Visit==\nTimarpur also bears the distinction of housing a 100-year-old plus market. The market (known as the Old Market) was established when Delhi was declared the capital during the British Raj in 1911. Yet the market has not seen development.\n\nTimarpur is surrounded by many tourist attractions like the northern ridge near the North Campus of [[University_of_Delhi|Delhi University]]. The area holds a forest where people come to jog and exercise. It was at one time used by the British armed forces during the British Raj. The flagstaff tower there was used by British families as a hiding spot during the Great Indian Mutiny of 1857. The Mutiny Memorial is also situated near the ridge and is an example of the British architecture that was used in India at that time.{{According to whom|date=July 2019}} It was built in memory of the British soldiers who were killed during the mutiny of 1857.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} Next to the Mutiny Memorial, is an Ashoka pillar that was shifted to Delhi by [[Firuz Shah Tughlaq|Feroz Shah Tughlaq]] (a king from the Tughlaq Dynasty).{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nApart from the historic monuments, Choudhary Sweets (now closed), and the Darvesh Restaurant are some of the eating spaces in Timarpur.{{Relevance inline|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe Budh Bazaar, held every Wednesday inside the Central Government Flats, is a center of attraction.\n\nTimarpur dairy village of Gurjars which supplies milk to the number of locals.\n\n==Education and health facilities==\n[[File:Timarpur Park.jpg|thumb|200px|Triangular Park in the Z-Block of Timarpur]]\n\nThe education facilities of Timarpur are moderate. In total, there are eight schools in Timarpur, six of them government-owned and two privately owned. The area is well connected to the University of Delhi.{{According to whom|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe health facilities of Timarpur include the health center of INMAS which is the biggest and the most technically equipped thyroid center in India. However, the area includes only one dispensary{{Clarify|reason=what is meant by a dispensary?|date=July 2019}} owned by the Government of India. There are several privately owned clinics also present there.\n\n===Schools===\n\n* Arya Samaj Mandir\n* Massom Special School\n* Nagar Nigam Vidhyalaya\n* Patrachar Vidhyalaya\n* Sarvodaya Kanya Vidhyalaya\n* Sarvodaya Bal Vidhyalaya\n* Sarvodaya Vidhyalaya Lancers Road\n* Virendra Public School (private)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Delhi]]\n", "name_user": "Gdrged", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar correction \"there is local dairy\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timarpur"}
{"title_page": "Manuel del Valle", "text_new": "{{underconstruction}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name               = Manuel del Valle\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| office             = Mayor of [[Seville]]\n| term_start         = May 24, 1983\n| term_end           = June 30, 1991\n| predecessor        = {{ill|Luis Uru\u00f1uela|es}}\n| successor          = {{ill|Alejandro Rojas-Marcos|es}}\n| office2            = President of the [[Provincial Council of Seville]]\n| term_start2        = 1979\n| term_end2          = 1983\n| predecessor2       = [[Mariano Borrero]]\n| successor2         = [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Pino Mench\u00e9n]]\n| office3            = Member of the Seville City Council \n| term_start3        = May 3, 1979\n| term_end3          = June 17, 1991\n| predecessor3       = \n| successor3         = \n| office4            = [[Senate of Spain|Senator of Spain]] for [[Seville (Senate constituency)|Seville]]\n| term_start4        = 1979\n| term_end4          = 1982\n| predecessor4       = \n| successor4         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1939|11|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Seville]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2020|3|26|1939|11|10}}\n| death_place        = [[Seville]], [[Spain]]\n| party              = [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party|PSOE]]\n| spouse             = \n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| residence          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Seville]]\n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Lawyer<br>Politician\n| religion           = \n| signature          = \n}}\n\n'''Manuel del Valle Ar\u00e9valo''' (November 10, 1939 \u2013 March 26, 2020) was a Spanish lawyer and politician, and member of the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]] (PSOE) who served as Mayor of [[Seville]] from May 24, 1983, until June 30, 1991. Del Valle is credited with redesigning the city's modern [[infrastructure]] in preparation for [[Seville Expo '92]].<ref name=lr>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Fallece el ex alcalde de Sevilla Manuel del Valle |url=https://www.larazon.es/actualidad/20200326/wc27wjyo5fbqhbtlpmlp4xfj4i.html |work=[[La Razon]]  |publisher= |date=2020-03-26 |accessdate=2020-04-14 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326230346/https://www.larazon.es/actualidad/20200326/wc27wjyo5fbqhbtlpmlp4xfj4i.html |archivedate=2020-03-26 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=abc>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Muere Manuel del Valle, el exalcalde de Sevilla que redise\u00f1\u00f3 la ciudad |url=https://sevilla.abc.es/sevilla/sevi-muere-manuel-valle-exalcalde-sevilla-rediseno-ciudad-202003262158_noticia.html |work=[[ABC (newspaper)]]  |publisher= |date=2020-03-27 |accessdate=2020-04-14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414030349/https://sevilla.abc.es/sevilla/sevi-muere-manuel-valle-exalcalde-sevilla-rediseno-ciudad-202003262158_noticia.html |archivedate=2020-04-14 |url-status=live}}</ref> His achievements included the construction of the [[Seville-Santa Justa railway station]], a new railway layout within the city, the SE-30 ring road and other highways, and a series of new bridges.<ref name=abc/> \n\n==Biography==\nManuel del Valle was born in Seville on November 10, 1939. He graduated from the [[University of Seville]] and became an attorney specializing in [[labor law]]. He joined the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]] (PSOE), which has a stronghold in [[Andalusia]], during the 1970s.  \n\nFrom 1979 until 1983, Manuel del Valle served as the first democratically elected President of the [[Provincial Council of Seville]] (''Diputaci\u00f3n Provincial de Sevilla''), which governs the [[Province of Seville]] and its municipalities.<ref name=abc/> He also served in the national [[Senate of Spain]], representing Seville as a member of the [[PSOE]], from 1979 to 1982.<ref name=abc/>\n\nDuring the 1980s, it was announced that Seville would host the forthcoming [[Seville Expo '92]], to be held in 1992 to commemorate the 500th anniversary of [[Christopher Columbus]] reaching the [[Americas]]. In order to host such a large event, Seville would have upgrade and, in many cases, construct or rebuild the city's entire [[urban infrastructure]]. In response, Mayor del Valle launched the 1987 [[PGOU|Plan General de Ordenaci\u00f3n Urbana]] ([[PGOU]]) to modernize and re-draw the city's rail and road infrastructure.<ref name=abc/> The new plan replaced \n\nDel Valle remained active in a variety of civic, historical, and urban affairs organizations after leaving office. He chaired the El Monte Foundation and served as a member of the [[board of trustees]] for the [[Alc\u00e1zar of Seville]], the city's royal palace.<ref name=abc/> He also acted as co-president of the Civic Union of Southern Spain (''Uni\u00f3n C\u00edvica del Sur de Espa\u00f1a'')), or Civisur, an organization which seeks stronger business and political ties between Seville and [[M\u00e1laga]].<ref name=abc/> In September 2019, Seville Mayor [[Juan Espadas]] appointed Del Valle as the Mayor of the [[Alc\u00e1zar of Seville|Alc\u00e1zar ]], a position he held until his death in March 2020.<ref name=abc/>\n\nManuel del Valle died in Seville of [[leukemia]] on March 26, 2020, at the age of 81.<ref name=abc/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valle, Manuel del}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Seville]]}}}\n[[Category:Provincial Deputation Presidents of Spain]]\n[[Category:Seville city councillors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Spain]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1st Senate of Spain]]\n[[Category:Andalusian politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Seville alumni]]\n\n[[ar:\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0648\u064a\u0644 \u062f\u064a\u0644 \u06a4\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0631\u064a\u06a4\u0627\u0644\u0648]]\n[[es:Manuel del Valle Ar\u00e9valo]]\n", "text_old": "{{underconstruction}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name               = Manuel del Valle\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| office             = Mayor of [[Seville]]\n| term_start         = May 24, 1983\n| term_end           = June 30, 1991\n| predecessor        = {{ill|Luis Uru\u00f1uela|es}}\n| successor          = {{ill|Alejandro Rojas-Marcos|es}}\n| office2            = President of the [[Provincial Council of Seville]]\n| term_start2        = 1979\n| term_end2          = 1983\n| predecessor2       = [[Mariano Borrero]]\n| successor2         = [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Pino Mench\u00e9n]]\n| office3            = Member of the Seville City Council \n| term_start3        = May 3, 1979\n| term_end3          = June 17, 1991\n| predecessor3       = \n| successor3         = \n| office4            = [[Senate of Spain|Senator of Spain]] for [[Seville (Senate constituency)|Seville]]\n| term_start4        = 1979\n| term_end4          = 1982\n| predecessor4       = \n| successor4         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1939|11|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Seville]], [[Spain]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2020|3|26|1939|11|10}}\n| death_place        = [[Seville]], [[Spain]]\n| party              = [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party|PSOE]]\n| spouse             = \n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| residence          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Seville]]\n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Lawyer<br>Politician\n| religion           = \n| signature          = \n}}\n\n'''Manuel del Valle Ar\u00e9valo''' (November 10, 1939 \u2013 March 26, 2020) was a Spanish lawyer and politician, and member of the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]] (PSOE) who served as Mayor of [[Seville]] from May 24, 1983, until June 30, 1991. Del Valle is credited with redesigning the city's modern [[infrastructure]] in preparation for [[Seville Expo '92]].<ref name=lr>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Fallece el ex alcalde de Sevilla Manuel del Valle |url=https://www.larazon.es/actualidad/20200326/wc27